sec.p:
The cerithioidean family 
Potamididae
shows a close association with mangroves. The great majority of its approximately 40 living species occur in mangrove habitats, where they are variously dependent upon the plants for shelter, as a substrate or for food (e.g. 
Houbrick 1984
, 
1991
; 
Plaziat 1984
; 
Glaubrecht 1997
; 
Willan 2013
; 
Reid 2014
). This ecological association has a long evolutionary history and is believed to have been characteristic of the family since its origin in the Tethyan realm during the Eocene (

Reid 
et al.
2008

).

Molecular methods are now routinely used for the discovery, delimitation and even diagnosis of species. Among cerithioidean gastropods such methods have been particularly important, because shells are of generalized form, often show confusing intraspecific variation and because the males are aphallate (therefore lacking the genital characters that are diagnostic in some other gastropod groups). In some cerithioideans, particularly the freshwater species, phylogeographic studies using mitochondrial markers have often revealed complex patterns involving non-monophyly of taxonomic species. While this may sometimes reflect inadequate taxonomy of cryptic species, it may also be due to retention of ancient haplotypes, incomplete lineage sorting in recent or rapid radiations, introgressive hybridization between species, and dispersal among relatively isolated river drainage systems (e.g. Köhler & Deein 2010 ;
Miura et al . 2013
). Within the Central American radiation of Cerithideopsis , a complex phylogeographic pattern has been explained by dispersal across the Panamanian Isthmus between the Pacific and Atlantic coasts, possibly the result of transport by migratory birds (
Miura et al . 2012
). However, in the marine and brackish genus Cerithidea in the IWP, a combination of molecular delimitation of species, morphological characters and geographical distribution has provided a partial resolution of a taxonomically confused group (
Reid et al . 2013
, 2014 ). This integrative approach has increased the number of recognized Cerithidea species
from ten to fifteen. So far, molecular sampling of Cerithideopsis (henceforward ‘ C. ’) ‘ largillierti ’ has been limited. Haplotype frequencies have been found to be similar in China and Japan (
Kojima et al . 2006
) and haplotype diversity reported as low in Korea (
Kamimura et al . 2010
). However,
Reid et al . (2008)
found a K2P (Kimura 2-parameter genetic distance) divergence for COI of 15% between two individuals each from Japan and Australia , and suggested that these might belong to different species. A revision appears to be required.

Growth is more or less indeterminate in the three Cerithideopsis species
included here. The axial sculpture of the final whorl is weaker than that on the spire whorls and one or more swollen varices usually develop somewhere on the last whorl. One or two varices may also be present on the two preceding whorls. Unlike some other potamidids, e.g. Cerithidea , there is not a stereotyped sequence of formation of a ‘ventrolateral’ varix followed by substantial flaring and thickening of the adult aperture. Instead, the apertural lip is only slightly thickened and flared, and growth may be resumed for a short period, leaving a ‘previous lip’ or series of strong growth lines (
). Varices are swollen and rounded, appearing to be formed from fusion of two axial ribs, whereas previous lips are sharply raised (compare varix on penultimate whorl and previous lip on final whorl in
).

The sculpture of the shell consists of regular axial ribs, which become weak and irregular on the final whorl. In some populations of 
C. australiensis
there is evidence of damage by shell-crushing crabs; the final whorl is often broken away as far as a varix. The shell that is regrown following such damage is often smooth, lacking the axial ribs of undamaged shells. For both these reasons the number of axial ribs is counted on the penultimate whorl (i.e. from the point of junction with the outer apertural lip to one revolution back from this point). Spiral cords are visible on the earliest whorls, but become obsolete with growth. The periphery of the final whorl is considered to be the junction of the sides of the whorl and the shell base; it corresponds to the line of suture between successive whorls on the spire (not the point furthest from the axis of coiling). The periphery is marked by the outermost of two enlarged cords, which are part of the series of cords or threads counted on the base of the shell (clearly visible in 

). The outermost basal cord is usually just visible in the deep suture between succeeding whorls (

). The shell is covered by a thick periostracum, which is marked by fine spiral microstriae, some of which bear short projections or bristles (

), but the periostracum is easily worn away and is rapidly lost from dead shells.

Distribution records and habitat.
The distribution records plotted on the map are based on personally verified museum collections and, in one case, on a reliable literature record. The records given in the text are of selected localities and range end-points and are not complete lists of material examined (these are available upon request and have been deposited in 
NHMUK
). Notes on habitat and ecology are based on personal observation unless otherwise acknowledged. Habitats are described with reference to the predominant genera of mangrove trees, which often show a characteristic zonation from seaward to landward sides in broad, undamaged mangrove stands (e.g. 
Macnae 1968
; 
Lozouet & Plaziat 2008
).

A statistical method was used to define species-level clusters in the COI tree. An ultrametric tree was generated in BEAST (v. 1.6.1, 
Drummond & Rambaut 2007
) and to find significant clusters within the tree the GMYC function from the SPLITS package (
Ezard, Fujisawa & Barraclough 2009
) in R (R 
Development Core Team 2009
) was applied (see detailed description by 

Reid 
et al
. 2013

). As further evidence for species delimitation, the uncorrected pairwise distances over all pairs of COI sequences were estimated among and within clusters using MEGA5 (Tamura 
et al
. 2011) and the nuclear 28S gene was examined for fixed differences.

Potential scale reduction factor (PSRF) values for the MrBayes analyses were less than 1.00 and effective sample sizes (ESS) were greater than 1000, indicating that all trees had reached stationarity. The ingroup of Cerithideopsis was monophyletic in all MrBayes analyses (PP = 1;
for COI, other trees not shown in full). The three eastern Pacific and Atlantic species ( C. californica , C. montagnei and C. scalariformis ) were monophyletic in all analyses (PP = 1), although only C. montagnei and C. californica were represented in the 16S analysis (
). Monophyly of the three Indo-West Pacific species was supported (PP = 1) in all but the 16S analysis. Monophyly of C. australiensis was strongly supported (PP ≥ 0.97) in the COI and all-gene analyses. Monophyly of C. largillierti was strongly supported (PP ≥ 0.95) in the COI and 16S analyses. Monophyly of C. malayensis was strongly supported (PP ≥ 0.95) in all except the COI analysis (PP = 0.91). In all analyses the sister relationship of C. largillierti and C. malayensis was strongly supported (PP ≥ 0.96).

tp:treatment-sec.p:
The three western Atlantic species of Cerithideopsis are C. pliculosa , C. costata and C. scalariformis ; these are relatively well known ( Bequaert 1942 ; Abbott 1974 ). Traditionally, six species have been accepted on the American west coast ( Keen 1971 ; Abbott 1974 ), but a recent molecular study (
Miura et al . 2010
) has suggested that this should be reduced to three: C. californica , C. montagnei and C. pulchra (C.B. Adams, 1852)
. Molecular discrimination of the American species is complicated by two cases of dispersal across the Panamanian Isthmus and subsequent introgression of mitochondrial haplotypes (
Miura et al. 2012
).

The six Cerithideopsis species
from the eastern Pacific and western Atlantic, and the three from the IWP described here, form two sister clades (
Reid et al . 2008
;
Miura et al . 2010
;
). Several morphological characters are restricted to the IWP species, including the thick periostracum, the absence of a strongly thickened and flared peristome, and the yellow markings of the living animal—contrasting with the brown to black animals described by Bright (1958) in C. californica and Houbrick (1984) in C. scalariformis . The deeper phylogeny of the family (
Reid et al . 2008
) suggests that these are likely synapomorphies.

Cerithium (Potamides) largilliertiPhilippi, 1848: 20 ( China ; neotype here designated NHMUK 20130431/1, Shanghai , China ,
). Philippi, 1849: 15 , Cerithium pl. 1, fig. 7 (cited as fig. 6 in error, p. 15;
herein).

Taxonomic history. The original description by Philippi (1848) was brief and he only figured the species later ( Philippi 1849 ). This may explain why Adams (1855) listed it as a distinct species in his monograph on Cerithidea , while also naming Cerithidea fortunei . The synonymy of these two names was noted by Sowerby (1855) , although he erroneously considered both to be synonyms of Cerithium montagnei (= C. montagnei ), a species from the Pacific coast of Central America. This error was pointed out by Carpenter (1857: 343) , but Cerithium largillierti was still listed under Cerithidea montagnei by Sowerby (1866) and Tryon (1887) . Meanwhile, Cerithidea fortunei continued to be widely used as the name of the present species ( Sowerby 1866 ; Tryon 1887 ; Fischer & Dautzenberg 1904 ; Iwakawa 1919 ). The name Cerithidea largillierti was reinstated by Dautzenberg & Fischer (1905) and thereafter this specific name has been almost universally used. There has been occasional misidentification as ‘ Cerithidea ornata ’ ( Yoo 1995 ;
Min et al . 2004
).

No type material of Cerithium largillierti has been traced (not present in MNHN, ZMB or SMF, which all contain some specimens of other species collected by Largilliert and/or described by Philippi). Philippi’s (1849) figure could serve as lectotype , but is not clearly drawn (
) and an actual specimen is desirable. Therefore, a shell from Shanghai is here designated the neotype (NHMUK 20130431/1;
). This shell is also one of the syntypes of C. fortunei A. Adams, 1855 . To avoid any possible confusion, and to reinforce the synonymy, this specimen is also designated the lectotype of C. fortunei .

Shell (

):

H = 
23.9–35.9 mm
. Shape elongated conical (H/B = 2.17–2.42, SH = 2.88–3.31); not routinely decollate, 9–11 whorls remaining in well preserved shells, but apex and protoconch always eroded. Spire whorls rounded, suture distinct; spire profile slightly convex, slightly concave towards apex; periphery rounded; relatively solid. Adult lip only slightly thickened, not flared; sometimes 1–2 previous lips on final whorl; apertural margin sinuous in side view; anterior canal a weak notch. Sculpture on spire of straight axial ribs, usually becoming curved (opisthocyrt) on last 2–3 whorls, ribs rounded, ribs and interspaces of similar width, 20–26 ribs on penultimate whorl, ribs becoming weaker and irregular on final whorl; 3–6 spiral cords on smallest apical whorls if well preserved, macroscopic spiral sculpture usually absent above periphery of larger whorls, sometimes 10–13 weak spiral elements visible between axial ribs on last 2 whorls; base with 8–9 cords, of which two at periphery are strong, with marked groove between, those towards columella becoming smaller. No ventrolateral varix, but 0–2 indistinct or prominently raised and rounded varices may be present at any point on last 2 whorls (

). Surface with spiral microstriae on thick periostracum, short periostracal fringe or bristles remaining on larger striae (i.e. 10–13 striae macroscopically visible above periphery) if well preserved; shiny where periostracum worn away; surface often covered by thick black concretion, presumably of microscopic algae and sediment. Colour: brown, with pale band just above periphery and another at shoulder, often indistinct beneath periostracum; aperture brown with indistinct pale bands.

