sec.p:
The allopatric distribution of the three species is consistent with the orthodox view that the prevailing mode of speciation in tropical shallow-water marine gastropods is allopatric (e.g. Williams & Reid 2004 ; Meyer, Geller & Paulay 2005 ; Frey 2010 ;
Claremont et al . 2011
;
Williams et al . 2011
; but see Krug 2011 ). No attempt has been made to estimate divergence times in the analysis presented here, because the fossil record of Cerithideopsis is so sparse (
Reid et al . 2008
). In a larger analysis of diversification throughout the Potamididae , the divergence of C. largillierti from C. malayensis has been estimated as 4.5 (1.7–8.3) Ma, and that of C. australiensis from the other two at 13.0 (6.4–21.3) Ma (BEAST analysis by D.G. Reid & M. Claremont, unpublished; 95% highest posterior density intervals in parentheses). The uncertainty in the dates is considerable, but evidently the divergences are not very recent; at the least they predate the Pleistocene glaciations. The maintenance of allopatry over such a long period is remarkable, especially in view of the fact that recolonization across the Sunda Shelf by C. malayensis must have occurred in the 17,000 years since the end of the last glacial low sea-level stand, showing that range expansion can occur rapidly. This has led to the suggestion that ‘mosaic’ distributions of this kind are maintained at least in part by competitive exclusion (
Reid et al . 2013
).

Increasingly, the wide geographical distributions once thought to be typical of marine organisms in the IWP province are being tested and challenged by molecular data. Some wide distributions have been confirmed, particularly among species with relatively long planktotrophic larval lives (e.g. some Nerita spp. Frey 2010 ; some Littoraria spp.
,
Reid et al . 2010
). However, it is becoming clear that, among those with shorter larval duration, a mosaic-type pattern of narrowly allopatric ranges among closely related species is common ( Paulay & Meyer 2002 ; Williams & Reid 2004 ;
Meyer et al . 2005
;
Reid et al . 2013
). The species of Cerithideopsis in the western Atlantic and eastern Pacific have nonplanktotrophic development or short larval lives (see Remarks on genus, above) so, if development is similar in the IWP members of the genus, the allopatric mosaic shown by the C. largillierti group is consistent with this emerging generalization.

